    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen deleting text on a line with diagnostics, with my fairly involved config, I can fairly reliably reproduce the following error:\n\n```\n                      W10: Warning: Changing a readonly file\n                     Lua callback: ...5/usr/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_changetracking.lua:305: attempt to index local 'buf_state' (a nil value)\nstack traceback:\n\t...5/usr/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_changetracking.lua:305: in function 'send_changes_for_group'\n\t...5/usr/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_changetracking.lua:348: in function 'send_changes'\n\t/snap/nvim/4475/usr/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua:918: in function </snap/nvim/4475/usr/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua:912>\n```\n\nLooking at that section of send_changes_for_group, we see:\n```lua\n  local buf_state = state.buffers[bufnr]\n  buf_state.needs_flush = true\n```\n\nInterestingly, on lines 362-363, in M.flush, we see the following more defensively written code:\n\n```lua\n    local buf_state = state.buffers[bufnr] or {}\n    reset_timer(buf_state)\n```\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nReproduction with a minimal config is not currently practical, I definitely understand if this gets the bug ignored, however...\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo errors occur during normal use.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-1565+gb80d390765 (installed via snap)\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNo.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu Linux, 25.04 with kernel 6.17.1\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nzterm, a libvte terminal\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nsnap",
