            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I found this issue using neovim 0.11.5. Here is how I can reproduce it\n\n1. Create a `init.lua` (or any name).\n\n2. Add this content to the file. Ensure you have at least 1 lsp configured in `after/lsp`.\n\n```lua\n-- init.lua\n\n-- Issue only when callback is inside this autocmd\n-- not an issue when called directly\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('UIEnter', {\n  callback = vim.schedule_wrap(function()\n    local lsp_servers = {}\n    for _, file in ipairs(vim.api.nvim_get_runtime_file('after/lsp/*', true)) do\n      local name = vim.fn.fnamemodify(file, ':t:r')\n      table.insert(lsp_servers, name)\n    end\n\n    vim.lsp.enable(lsp_servers)\n  end),\n})\n```\n\n3. Launch neovim using the file as the config file.\n\n```bash\nnvim -u init.lua\n```\n\n4. Open a file. E.g. `:e some_file` . Any file, it doesn't have to have attach any lsp. I used `.gitignore` for example.\n5. Observe error\n\n<img width=\"3399\" height=\"1912\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f10946ca-ef43-419c-b488-3260c760a2ac\" />\n\n\n\nNotice that this only errors on WSL. It didn't happen on native windows. I haven't tried on base linux.\n\nSeparately, while looking into this I found that this snippet shows an error by just starting neovim. Reproducible in both WSL and windows.\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('UIEnter', {\n  callback = vim.schedule_wrap(function()\n    vim.lsp.enable({})\n  end),\n})\n```\n\n<img width=\"3399\" height=\"1886\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c808ea6e-a4ce-41ab-9881-75259a6b77ba\" />\n\n```\nError executing vim.schedule lua callback: ...ovim-unwrapped-0.11.5/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua:636: Vim:E216: No such group or event: nvim.lsp.enable FileType stack traceback:\n        [C]: in function 'doautoall'\n        ...ovim-unwrapped-0.11.5/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp.lua:636: in function 'enable'\n        /home/eduardo/.config/vscode-nvim/test.lua:22: in function ''\n        vim/_editor.lua: in function <vim/_editor.lua:0>\n```\n\n---\n\nI want to clarify I don't necessarily **need** to defer the lsp start that way. I was simply experimenting as I'm trying to prevent a hang when opening/closing neovim too fast which I believe it is related to lsp initialization but I haven't confirmed anything yet. So not worth concerning about that.\n\nLet me know if you need other information.",
